summary: that moment of resignation when Tony turns off the recorder and powers down the helmet for what he believes is the last time.....
body:
that moment of resignation when Tony turns off the recorder and powers down the helmet for what he believes is the last time.. He’s accepted he’s going to die. He’s accepted he’s never going to see Pepper again. He’s accepted that he will never hold the kid he wanted, he’ll never have the family he came so close to getting, the wedding that slipped right from between his fingers. Its all gone now, replaced by an unshakable grief, shallow breaths that pierce his lungs and a weight on his shoulders even heavier than before. The dull ache of starvation, of endless desolation, the dryness in his mouth and not just from dehydration. He is stranded in space in the middle of nowhere and his heart is aching for the son he lost and the daughter he never had— the memories of promised domesticity seems so distant now. That life has forsaken him. It aches in his bones and even though there’s no shrapnel in his chest, no arc reactor to keep the pieces from tearing into his heart, the agony he feels is too real to be phantom pain. Its the guilt of feeling like he didn’t do enough, riddled with the hopelessness that shadows his every breath.. the ghost of a voice ringing in his ears like a broken record, “You could’ve saved them. Why didn’t you do more?” Its eats away at him from the inside, bringing his strength crashing to its knees and his sanity falling apart like a house of cards.

His tear ducts have long run dry and he can’t tell if the pain in his muscles is in his imagination or if its an actual physical ache. All he knows is that his death will be slow, it will be painful and it will end in the middle of nowhere, in the the nothingness of space. What’s worse.. he actually believes he deserves it.
